One use of acetone's capacity to dissolve plastic is what are called "acetate peals". You take a rock (I've done it with carbonates, but you can do it with silicates if you can find the right acid), cut it, and polish one side. Then you dip that polished side VERY BREIFLY into a solvent. Once the solvent is dry, you dip the rock into acetone, then press it onto an acetate sheet. You hold it there for a second, then remove the rock (pulling it straight up). What's left behind, if you do it right, is an impression of the rock, showing all the grains, fossils, etc.

The great thing about this method is that once you etch the rock, you can make as many acetate peals as you want. And since they each show what's in the rock, you can ship these acetate peals to various researchers. I've used them to count the number of brachiopods in a chunk of limestone, for example--a few of us counted the number in the same rock, to test various counting methods. It also saves a lot of time compared to traditional thin sections, because you only have to polish one side of the rock.

Take the acetone PS slime and dissolve that in gasoline to make slightly faster burning, hotter napalm with reduced viscosity.  Probably an excellent flamethrower ammunition when fully dissolved as it serves as a compromise between the viscosity of thicker and slower burning napalms (which burn for a very long time but at a lower temperature with a longer range) and pure fuel (which has a very short range and burns really hotly).  A mid-range, but high heat ammunition for a flamethrower is exactly the tool to use to rid your old shed of killer bees (assuming you don't care about the shed either), or  get rid of incoming locust swarms (as long as you wear fire hazard gear).

I melt normal styrene (from the model kit runners), and polystyrene foam in acetone, until no more will dissolve - I keep this resultant slurry in a small screwtop jar, and use it as a filler on styrene kits: it can be used to repair holes, and build up parts. It's been used for ages here in the UK, and is generally known as 'goop'. Once it dries, it can be worked and painted exactly like normal styrene. The action of a solvent on polystyrene foam is also how, in the movie 'Alien', they show the acid blood of the 'Facehugger' burn through the Nostromo's deck plates, when they try to remove it from Kane's face with a laser scalpel.
